"Bangladesh is one of the first signatories to the Convention for the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women (CEDAW). The constitution of the country specifically ensures equal rights for women in all spheres of life. The Bangladeshi Government has, however, failed to implement most of the related laws and agreements. Gender disparity remains one of the dominant concerns of women in Bangladesh. Within the industrial sector, basic services for women employees and entrepreneurs, such as day-care facilities, are lacking and seriously hamper their economic participation and development. Amongst others, no system is in place for taking care of children during women’s work period. Many women in Bangladesh find employment in the Ready Made Garment (RMG) sector, but less than 500 RMG factories, on a total of more than 5000, offer day-care services. This situation violates the Bangladesh Labour Act of 2006, which states that female workers have rights to child-care facilities managed by trained and experienced female caregivers.  This proposed project is expected to contribute to create a network of quality day-care facilities at RMG factories, which in turn, will create employability for women’s caregivers and entrepreneurs and will ensure RMG factories are compliant with the Labour Act. This project aims at accomplishing these objectives through: 1. training and certifying female caregivers and their supervisors; 2. training women entrepreneurs to run these day-care centres as sustainable businesses; 3. developing learning strategies to motivate the private sector to provide quality day-care services at the factories. Considering the practical focus of the requested know-how in this project, potential bidders are strongly encouraged to engage Universities of Applied Sciences, and Regional Training Centres (ROC’s) in their consortia for the implementation of the project. Besides, potential bidders are encouraged to liaise with local/regional consultants and expertise, given the specific social and cultural context of the training and capacity needs."

Agricultural Colleges (TVET-level) in Ghana are tasked to train middle-level personnel to provide technical support and extension services to farmers. A major challenge confronting the Agricultural Colleges relates to lack of practical skills by teaching staff and students. The courses offered at the colleges take private sector and market needs insufficiently into consideration. Gender-concerns are not systematically addressed, both at educational level as at organisational level. Even though the colleges are managed professionally, strengthening is needed in several areas such as leadership and human resource-management. The project therefore aims to strengthen both the educational and organisational capacity of agricultural colleges to deliver male and female graduates that meet labour market and gender needs. In addition, staff of three farmer institutes will participate in trainings so as to ensure a similar educational approach for future middle-level staff working with medium to small scale farmers.
